{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8c8ac843-7b73-43a7-a8ff-180baace274a","content":"I should clarify — CLR activation logs and a `NullReferenceException` are two different things:\n\n- **CLR activation logs** diagnose which .NET Framework runtime version gets loaded by `mscoree.dll` (the shim). They help when the *wrong runtime loads*, or *no runtime loads at all*.\n- A **NullReferenceException** is a managed code bug — a null reference is being dereferenced at runtime. Activation logs won't reveal that.\n\n**What you likely need instead:**\n1. **The stack trace** from the exception — it will point to the exact line.\n2. **A debugger** (Visual Studio, `dotnet-dump`, or WinDbg) to inspect the null reference.\n3. If the crash happens *before* managed code runs, then activation logs might be relevant.\n\n**Can you share:**\n- The full exception message and stack trace?\n- Does the app fail to start entirely, or does it start and then crash?\n- Is this .NET Framework or modern .NET (5+/6+/8+)?\n\nIf you do believe this is a runtime activation issue (e.g., the app can't find or load the CLR at all), I can invoke the CLR activation debugging skill. Just let me know!","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"07bc8d0a-2989-47ae-9887-dec807ad766b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. They mention CLR activation logs specifically. Let me check if the relevant skill is available - yes, there's a \"clr-activation-debugging\" skill that diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs.\n\nLet me invoke that skill.","outputTokens":387,"requestId":"9423:634EC:18E44C9:1C5FDBF:69E82412"},"id":"c8e70b1b-03f4-4307-b213-f925150a1635","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:27:57.093Z","parentId":"c75ca135-eff5-4443-966c-330609d68cc8"}
